Material Information Summary

Operational Update & Key Metrics

  • High-grade ore processing commenced at Kayelekera Uranium Project, with first production expected this quarter.
  • Power grid connection construction starts, targeting completion by end-CY2026; estimated to reduce costs by US$5–6/lb (vs. diesel).
  • US$8.5M equipment finance facility secured (5-year term, <10% interest) for mobile/mining equipment.
  • Tailings Storage Facility (TSF) expansion accelerated; Phase 1A/B capex ~US$19.5M (combined, vs. initial US$4M for Phase 1A).
  • Restart capital budget remains on track (US$50M); unaudited cash balance of A$75.9M (end-June 2025), no debt drawn.

Key Implication

Accelerated infrastructure spending may impact near-term cash flow, but grid power and TSF optimization support long-term cost reduction (~US$5–6/lb savings) and operational scalability.

Material Information Summary – Robex Resources Inc. (ASX: RXR)

1. Capital Raising & ASX Listing

  • IPO Completion: Raised A$120M (before costs) via ASX listing (38.6M CDIs at A$3.11) on 5 June 2025.
  • Use of Proceeds: Funds Kiniéro Gold Project development and corporate growth.

2. Kiniéro Gold Project (Guinea) – Construction & Development

  • On Schedule/Budget: First gold pour targeted Q4 2025 (December).
  • Key Progress:
  • CIL tanks (Train A completed), SAG mill installation commenced.
  • CAPEX: CAD$65.3M spent in Q2 (YTD: CAD$99.2M); total project budget CAD$210–225M.
  • Drilling: 61,700m completed; high-grade intercepts (e.g., 14m @ 11.40g/t Au).

3. Nampala Mine (Mali) – Operational Highlights

  • Production: 11,736oz gold produced, 13,104oz sold in Q2.
  • Costs: All-in sustaining cost (AISC) rose to CAD$2,125/oz (vs. CAD$1,171/oz in Q2 2024) due to higher royalties.
  • Guidance: Full-year FY25 production 46,000–48,000oz (on track).

4. Corporate & Financial Updates

  • Debt Facility: US$130M Sprott facility (CAD$177.9M); US$25M drawn in March 2025.
  • Capital Structure: Shares outstanding increased to 218.2M (from 168.5M) post-IPO and Sycamore settlement.
  • Sycamore Settlement: Issued 10.1M shares + 12.5M warrants (CAD$2.75 strike) to resolve acquisition dispute; recognized CAD$21.6M expense.

5. Forward Guidance

  • Nampala: FY25 AISC <CAD$2,000/oz (currently CAD$2,228/oz YTD).
  • Kiniéro: Pre-production CAPEX CAD$33–35M; total CAPEX CAD$210–225M.

Excluded: Routine safety/environmental updates, non-material drilling results, and operational minutiae.
Next Key Catalyst: Kiniéro commissioning (Q4 2025).

Material Information Summary: Astral Resources (ASX: AAR) – Quarterly Report (June 2025)

1. Mandilla Pre-Feasibility Study (PFS) Highlights

  • Production target: 1.4Moz gold over 19 years (LoM).
  • Key metrics (base case, gold price A$4,250/oz):
  • Pre-tax NPV8: ~A$1.4B.
  • Free cash flow: ~A$2.8B.
  • Payback period: <1 year.
  • AISC: A$2,085/oz.
  • Maiden Ore Reserve: 36.6Mt at 0.9g/t Au (1.1Moz).

2. Mineral Resource Updates

  • Mandilla MRE: 42Mt at 1.1g/t Au (1.43Moz).
  • Group MRE (incl. Spargoville): 50Mt at 1.1g/t Au (1.76Moz).

3. Exploration & Drilling

  • Mandilla: 3,961m RC drilling (Iris infill, Hestia extensional).
  • Feysville: 2,914m RC drilling (Kamperman deposit); high recoveries (avg. 98%) in metallurgical tests.
  • Spargoville: 6,212m RC drilling (Spargoville Shear Zone).

4. Corporate & Financials

  • Cash balance: A$18.6M (30 June 2025).
  • Maximus acquisition: Completed 2 May 2025 (23.6M shares issued).
  • Quarterly cash outflow: A$4.0M (61% exploration, 18% Maximus).

5. Forward Work Plan

  • Definitive Feasibility Study (DFS): Targeted completion by June 2026; Final Investment Decision (FID) by Q3 2026.
  • Exploration focus: Resource conversion, extensional drilling, greenfields targets.

6. Key Risks/Catalysts

  • Gold price sensitivity: NPV8 rises to A$2.0B at A$5,000/oz.
  • Permitting & financing: Discussions ongoing for water supply, debt advisory.

Additional Notes

  • No capital raising or material operational disruptions disclosed.
  • Mineral Resources/Ore Reserves: JORC-compliant; see Tables 4–5 in announcement for full breakdown.

Conclusion: Strong PFS metrics and growing resource base support advancement toward DFS, with liquidity sufficient for near-term activities.
